body:
@AudriusButkevicius I occasionally move data from one place to another and don't want to worry about all the configs and preferences to be updated. Thats why I use symlinks a lot. But pointing it to the base directory is what I currently use as a workaround.

@calmh I have no expertise about how microsoft systems behave about trailing slashes but I would love to see such a change! I don't have any experience in writing go but would try my best to help testing.

btw: amazing response times ;)

Essentially this:

``` diff
diff --git a/lib/config/config.go b/lib/config/config.go
index bd19c32..cee6056 100644
--- a/lib/config/config.go
+++ b/lib/config/config.go
@@ -360,7 +360,7 @@ func (cfg *Configuration) prepare(myID protocol.DeviceID) {
                // C:\somedir\ ->  C:\somedir\\   ->  C:\somedir
                // This way in the tests, we get away without OS specific separators
                // in the test configs.
-               folder.RawPath = filepath.Dir(folder.RawPath + string(filepath.Separator))
+               folder.RawPath = filepath.Dir(folder.RawPath+string(filepath.Separator)) + string(filepath.Separator)

                if folder.ID == "" {
                        folder.ID = "default"
```

That looks kind of nonsensical, adding and stripping and adding the slash, but it does ensure the end result regardless of the input I think.
